  "output": "# Database Anomaly Diagnosis ‚Äî Educational System (MARBLE)\r\n\r\n> **Note:** The \"educational system\" narrative (students/courses/enrollments/payments) is a **red herring**. Those tables exist but are empty. The real anomaly is concentrated entirely in `table1`, a 1421 MB, 2,000,000-row table with 22 wide columns and **zero indexes**.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n## Final Diagnosis\r\n\r\n```\r\nINSERT_LARGE_DATA\r\nFETCH_LARGE_DATA\r\n```\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n## Symptoms\r\n\r\n| Symptom | Observed Value |\r\n|---|---|\r\n| Slow queries | 2‚Äì5 seconds per call (pg_stat_statements) |\r\n| Full-table sequential scans on table1 | 376 seq_scans, 384,020,015 tuples read |\r\n| Enormous read amplification | tup_returned 385,190,564 vs tup_fetched 428,878 ‚Äî **~898:1 ratio** |\r\n| Heavy disk I/O | 31,226,847 blocks read (pg_stat_database.blks_read) |\r\n| Massive temp spills | 67 temp files, **6,037 MB** (6,337,257,472 bytes) temp bytes |\r\n| No indexes on the heaviest table | table1 has 0 indexes; planner cannot avoid full scans |\r\n| Planner stats absent | last_analyze IS NULL on table1 ‚Äî planner is flying blind |\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n## Root Cause Analysis\r\n\r\n### INSERT_LARGE_DATA\r\n\r\nA bulk load of 2,000,000 wide rows was performed against `table1`, producing a 1421 MB monolithic heap with no supporting indexes.\r\n\r\n**Concrete evidence:**\r\n\r\n| Metric | Value | Source |\r\n|---|---|---|\r\n| Physical table size | **1421 MB** (1,489,920,000 bytes) | `pg_class` / `pg_total_relation_size()` |\r\n| Row count | **2,000,000 rows** | `pgstattuple` / `COUNT(*)` |\r\n| Column width | **22 columns** | `information_schema.columns` |\r\n| Heap packing density | **93.46%** | `pgstattuple.tuple_percent` |\r\n| Dead tuples | **0** | `pg_stat_user_tables.n_dead_tup` |\r\n| Live-tuple stat counter | 0 (`n_live_tup`) | `pg_stat_user_tables` ‚Äî counter bypassed |\r\n\r\nThe zero `n_live_tup` / `n_tup_ins` counters combined with 93.46% packing density and 0 dead tuples is the fingerprint of a **bulk COPY/restore** performed at database initialisation time, which bypasses live DML stat counters but physically fills the heap. The result is a 1.4 GB heap inserted in a single operation with no index maintenance, no partitioning, and no capacity planning.\r\n\r\n### FETCH_LARGE_DATA\r\n\r\nEvery query that touches `table1` must perform a full sequential scan because there are **zero indexes**. Queries consuming aggregates (`COUNT(DISTINCT ‚Ä¶)`, range predicates, sorted outputs) must materialise large intermediate result sets to disk as temp files.\r\n\r\n**Concrete evidence (spot-checked live against the DB):**\r\n\r\n| Metric | Value | Source |\r\n|---|---|---|\r\n| Sequential scans on table1 | **376** | `pg_stat_user_tables.seq_scan` |\r\n| Tuples read per scan cycle | **384,020,015** | `pg_stat_user_tables.seq_tup_read` |\r\n| DB-level tuples returned | **385,190,564** | `pg_stat_database.tup_returned` |\r\n| DB-level tuples fetched | **428,878** | `pg_stat_database.tup_fetched` |\r\n| Read amplification ratio | **~898:1** | tup_returned √∑ tup_fetched |\r\n| Disk blocks read | **31,226,847** | `pg_stat_database.blks_read` |\r\n| Temp files spilled | **67** | `pg_stat_database.temp_files` |\r\n| Temp bytes spilled | **6,337,257,472 (~6.04 GB)** | `pg_stat_database.temp_bytes` |\r\n| Indexes on table1 | **0** | `pg_indexes` / `pg_stat_user_indexes` |\r\n| Query latency | **2‚Äì5 seconds/call** | `pg_stat_statements` |\r\n\r\nA 898:1 ratio of rows returned vs rows actually consumed by the client is unambiguous evidence that the database is dragging entire table scans across the wire (or into aggregation pipelines) for every query. Without indexes, `work_mem` is exhausted and operators spill 6 GB to temp files across 67 files.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n## Evidence Table\r\n\r\n| Candidate Cause | Verdict | Confidence | Key Evidence |\r\n|---|---|---|---|\r\n| **INSERT_LARGE_DATA** | **PRESENT** | 90% | 2M rows / 1421 MB / 93.46% packing / 0 dead tuples / n_tup_ins bypassed ‚Äî classic bulk COPY at init (`pg_class`, `pgstattuple`, `pg_stat_user_tables`) |\r\n| **FETCH_LARGE_DATA** | **PRESENT** | 99% | 376 seq_scans, 384M tuples read, 898:1 tup_returned:tup_fetched, 31M blks_read, 6 GB temp spill, 2‚Äì5 s queries, 0 indexes on table1 (`pg_stat_user_tables`, `pg_stat_database`, `pg_stat_statements`, `pg_indexes`) |\r\n| VACUUM | **ABSENT** | 95% | n_dead_tup=0, n_tup_upd=0, n_tup_del=0, no vacuum process in `pg_stat_progress_vacuum` or `pg_stat_activity`; NULL last_autovacuum is benign |\r\n| LOCK_CONTENTION | **ABSENT** | 99% | 0 ungranted lock rows in `pg_locks`, 0 deadlocks in `pg_stat_database`, 0 lock-waiting sessions in `pg_stat_activity` |\r\n| REDUNDANT_INDEX | **ABSENT** | 99% | 11 indexes across other tables, each on a distinct column; table1 has 0 indexes ‚Äî the problem is the opposite (`pg_stat_user_indexes`, `pg_indexes`) |\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n## Ruled Out\r\n\r\n**VACUUM** ‚Äî There is nothing to vacuum. `pg_stat_user_tables` reports `n_dead_tup = 0` and `n_tup_del = 0` across all tables. No UPDATE or DELETE has ever run against the dataset. `pg_stat_progress_vacuum` shows no in-progress vacuum operations, and `last_autovacuum` being NULL is expected for a freshly loaded, never-modified table. VACUUM bloat is irrelevant when dead-tuple percentage is exactly zero.\r\n\r\n**LOCK_CONTENTION** ‚Äî A full scan of `pg_locks` shows zero rows with `granted = false`. `pg_stat_database.deadlocks = 0`. No session in `pg_stat_activity` is in a `lock` wait state. The workload appears to be read-heavy SELECT queries, which take share locks that do not contend with each other. Query latency is entirely attributable to I/O and temp spills, not lock waits.\r\n\r\n**REDUNDANT_INDEX** ‚Äî The 11 indexes that exist are on the music-streaming schema tables (`users`, `songs`, `plays`, etc.), each covering a distinct column (user_id, username, email, etc.) with no overlap. No duplicate or partially-overlapping index pairs were found in `pg_stat_user_indexes`. Crucially, `table1` ‚Äî the source of all performance pain ‚Äî has *zero* indexes; redundant indexes are the mirror-opposite problem and do not apply here.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n## Remediation Steps\r\n\r\n### Immediate (hours)\r\n\r\n1. **Create targeted indexes on table1** for all columns used in WHERE, JOIN, GROUP BY, and ORDER BY predicates. At minimum, cover the columns appearing in the top queries identified via `pg_stat_statements`. Example:\r\n   ```sql\r\n   CREATE INDEX CONCURRENTLY idx_table1_col1 ON table1 (col1);\r\n   ```\r\n   Use `CONCURRENTLY` to avoid locking the table during creation.\r\n\r\n2. **Run ANALYZE on table1** immediately ‚Äî `last_analyze` is NULL, meaning the query planner has no statistics and cannot make informed plan choices:\r\n   ```sql\r\n   ANALYZE table1;\r\n   ```\r\n\r\n3. **Increase `work_mem`** to reduce temp-file spills. The 67 temp files / 6 GB spill indicates hash aggregates and sort operators are exhausting the current `work_mem` setting. A per-session or global increase (e.g., `SET work_mem = '256MB'`) will trade RAM for eliminating the 6 GB disk I/O:\r\n   ```sql\r\n   ALTER SYSTEM SET work_mem = '256MB';\r\n   SELECT pg_reload_conf();\r\n   ```\r\n\r\n### Short-term (days)\r\n\r\n4. **Rewrite full-scan queries**: Replace `SELECT *` / `COUNT(DISTINCT ‚Ä¶)` full sweeps with indexed lookups, covering indexes, or pre-aggregated materialised views. Add `LIMIT` and keyset pagination to any query that can return large result sets.\r\n\r\n5. **Partition or archive table1**: At 1421 MB / 2M rows, range- or list-partitioning on a date/category column will allow partition pruning and reduce per-query scan scope. Archive historical partitions to cold storage if they are rarely queried.\r\n\r\n6. **Load large data in batches off-peak**: Future bulk loads should be split into batches (e.g., 100 K rows per transaction), executed during low-traffic windows, followed immediately by `ANALYZE` and index creation. Avoid single-transaction COPY of millions of rows in production.\r\n\r\n### Long-term (weeks)\r\n\r\n7. **Enable `pg_stat_statements`** (if not already) and set up alerting on: `seq_scan` growth rate, `temp_bytes > 100 MB`, and `tup_returned / tup_fetched > 100:1`.\r\n\r\n8. **Review `autovacuum` and `autoanalyze` settings** to ensure they trigger promptly after any future bulk loads (reduce `autovacuum_analyze_threshold` + `autovacuum_analyze_scale_factor`).\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n## Prevention Measures\r\n\r\n1. **Index strategy before bulk loads** ‚Äî define and create all necessary indexes *before* (or immediately after) a large data load. Document index requirements in the schema migration runbook.\r\n\r\n2. **Query review and pagination policy** ‚Äî enforce a code-review gate requiring that any query against tables > 100 MB must use an indexed predicate and return a bounded result set (`LIMIT` / keyset pagination). Reject `SELECT *` or unbounded aggregates on large tables.\r\n\r\n3. **Continuous monitoring on key ratios** ‚Äî instrument dashboards (Prometheus / pgBadger / CloudWatch) to alert when:\r\n   - `seq_scan` on any table > 1 GB increases by > 10/hour\r\n   - `temp_bytes` exceeds 500 MB/hour\r\n   - `tup_returned / tup_fetched` ratio exceeds 50:1\r\n\r\n4. **Post-load ANALYZE automation** ‚Äî add `ANALYZE <table>;` as a mandatory post-step in all ETL/migration pipelines. Consider a CI check that fails if `last_analyze` is NULL on tables > 10 MB after a migration run.\r\n\r\n5. **Capacity planning for large inserts** ‚Äî model storage and I/O impact of bulk loads in staging before production. A 2M-row, 22-column, 1.4 GB load with no indexes will saturate shared_buffers and generate significant I/O; plan maintenance windows accordingly.\r\n"
